N2  - This study focuses on the critical problem of simultaneous worker evacuation and equipment rescue during fire emergencies in high-speed rail beam yards. We propose an A3C-based multi-agent deep reinforcement learning framework with adaptive path planning, integrating dynamic obstacles modeling to simulate real-time fire spread and enabling decentralized training under limited field-of-view perception. Addressing the limitation of existing studies that focus on either evacuation or rescue, our model dynamically coordinates both by enabling agents to learn collision-free paths in a shared environment. Experiments show that the proposed approach enables real-time path adjustment, achieves over 85% success in dual-task execution, and offers greater robustness to fire spread uncertainties than traditional methods. Key contributions include: (1) A novel integration of dynamic obstacle modeling and decentralized multi-agent A3C training is proposed to enhance adaptability to real-world fire scenarios; (2) A dual-objective emergency strategy balancing human safety and equipment protection is optimized. © 2025 IEEE.
