N2  - With smartphones managing vast amounts of sensitive personal and financial data, they have become prime targets for cyber threats such as identity theft, fraud, and phishing. Traditional cybersecurity measures often fall short of detecting the intricate risks that arise within complex communication channels. This paper introduces the SMART (Smartphone Metadata Analysis for Recognizing Threats) model, a novel approach that combines Ra networks with natural language processing (NLP) to enhance cybercriminal detection by analyzing smartphone data. By focusing on social media interactions, messages, and call logs, the model uses advanced feature extraction and classification techniques to capture subtle indicators of malicious activity across varied data environments. In testing, the SMART model achieved a 98.93% accuracy rate, outperforming conventional approaches and other machine learning models. This study underscores the advantages of using NLP and behavior-based anomaly detection (BBAD) for detecting and interpreting criminal activities on mobile devices, offering a scalable, efficient solution that addresses real-world challenges in cybersecurity where data consistency may fluctuate. © 2025 IEEE.
