N2  - Under the guidance of the "dual carbon" strategic goal, the integration of the electricity and carbon markets is accelerating. Joint bidding strategies of market participants in this dual-market environment have become a key variable affecting the efficiency of resource allocation and emission reduction. Addressing the issues of information asymmetry and complex bidding behaviors in these markets, this paper constructs a multi-agent game model that incorporates the joint clearing mechanism of both. And it introduces a multi-agent reinforcement learning framework to optimize the bidding strategies of power generators and consumers. In the model, the electricity market aims to minimize social costs, while the carbon market aims to minimize emission trading costs. These two are coupled through carbon emission coefficients and quota constraints. Each market participant bids with the goal of maximizing revenue, and the parameters of their bidding functions constitute the action space for the agent. The system state encompasses key variables such as price, emissions, and quotas. This paper employs an independent Q-learning algorithm to train the agents and conducts sensitivity analyses under various scenarios, including carbon quotas on the generation side, quotas on the consumer side, and varying carbon emission coefficients. Simulation results demonstrate that carbon quotas and emission coefficients significantly affect the bidding behavior of market participants, market-clearing prices, and income distribution. Well-designed quota systems and pricing mechanisms are conducive to improving market efficiency and promoting synergies in emission reduction. This research provides a theoretical and empirical reference for the optimized regulation and intelligent decision-making in the joint electricity-carbon market. ©2025 IEEE.
