N2  - The increasing integration of distributed energy resources and the pursuit of carbon neutrality have highlighted the need for efficient and low-carbon dispatch strategies in microgrids. This study proposes an evolutionary multi-agent dispatch framework that jointly integrates the electricity, carbon, and green certificate (GC) markets. A coupling mechanism is developed to facilitate coordinated pricing and resource allocation across energy and environmental domains. The dynamic behavior of heterogeneous agents - including renewable generators, conventional units, and responsive users - is captured through an evolutionary game-based strategy updating process. A demand-side incentive mechanism, designed with consideration of user preferences and risk sensitivity, promotes active participation in GC trading. Simulation results on a benchmark microgrid demonstrate that the proposed method significantly reduces operational costs, enhances renewable energy utilization, and improves GC compliance. The proposed framework provides a practical pathway for sustainable microgrid operation and integrated market coordination. © 2025 IEEE.
