N2  - This paper presents a novel approach to multi-Agent swarm cooperative control using deep reinforcement learning enhanced with graph attention mechanisms. We propose a distributed cooperative control method that addresses practical challenges in complex scenarios, including limited communication, perception capabilities, and obstacle avoidance. The methodology incorporates three key innovations: First, we develop a distributed multi-Agent reinforcement learning framework with an experience sharing mechanism to improve sample utilization and policy convergence. Second, we integrate obstacle avoidance capabilities by designing specific reward functions and implementing double Q-learning to address value overestimation issues. Third, we enhance the network architecture with graph attention mechanisms to improve environmental perception and adaptive feature extraction. The algorithm is extensively tested in both numerical simulations and a high-fidelity physical simulation platform using unmanned aerial vehicles. Experimental results demonstrate that our approach effectively controls multi-Agent swarm behavior, successfully navigates obstacles, and shows robust adaptability to varying numbers of agents. The proposed method exhibits superior performance in terms of convergence speed, obstacle avoidance capability, and overall system stability compared to traditional approaches, making it particularly suitable for real-world applications in complex environments. © 2025 IEEE.
