N2  - A decision-making model for intelligent agents is proposed in this study, emphasizing the maximization of group utility to address the challenges of multi-agent decision-making in dynamic and partially observable environments. The model functions on the principle of agents collectively forming utility, thereby mitigating limitations arising from incomplete observations through shared utilities. By prioritizing the enhancement of group utility, the model facilitates the establishment of joint behavior and action plans for the agents. A representative experiment is conducted within the context of Pac-Man gameplay, where the ghosts aim to encircle the Pac-Man. Through controlled experiments, the cooperative decision-making capability of the model is assessed, revealing a significant improvement in the performance of the multi-agent system. The findings demonstrate that adopting a decision-making approach centered on group utility diminishes the constraints arising from individual agent observations, particularly within extensive search spaces. Consequently, the model proves beneficial in aiding multi-agent systems in efficiently accomplishing their designated tasks. © 2024 IEEE.
