N2  - In multi-agent reinforcement learning (MARL), effective collaboration and decision-making among agents are crucial for achieving complex tasks. Existing methods still face many challenges when dealing with large-scale agents and complex interactions, such as the non-stationarity of the environment, the scalability issues caused by the exponential growth of the joint action space, and the efficiency of information exchange among agents. Although existing methods utilize attention mechanisms to compute the action value function for more accurate credit allocation, they neglect to leverage attention in policy optimization, limiting agents' ability to dynamically adapt to others' behaviors. We propose an improved algorithm named Dual Attention Actor-Critic (DAAC). This algorithm introduces attention mechanisms in the policy gradient to enhance agents' decision-making capabilities in complex dynamic environments. Specifically, the attention mechanism in the policy gradient allows agents to dynamically assess the behaviors and potential intentions of other agents, thereby selecting more optimal actions. Experiments in two multi-agent particle environments with cooperative tasks demonstrated that DAAC converges faster than the existing method without sacrificing the scalability of multi-agent systems. © 2025 IEEE.
