N2  - This work introduces a new automated machine learning (ML)-based approach to multi-agent path planning that could revolutionise collision-free swarm motion in extremely dynamic settings. In addition to avoiding common problems like overestimation bias, slow learning, and sparse reward signals, our system significantly increases learning efficiency by utilising cutting-edge deep reinforcement learning (DRL) techniques like new duelling network architectures, double Q-learning, and an improved prioritised experience replay buffer. Our system provides real-time feedback and natural grid-based simulations, allowing users to see and manage multi-agent behaviour with remarkable accuracy. It is robustly interfaced with real-time human-machine interface (HMI) capabilities. Extensive experimental studies on a 9×9 grid with four autonomous robots demonstrate that our paradigm works better than current approaches with near-optimal path planning, a faster convergence speed, and significantly reduced collision rates. The technological robustness and practical usefulness of our paradigm for creating swarm robotics and multi-agent systems research are demonstrated by the detailed simulation workflows, rigorous numerical equations, and extensive comparative analysis table provided. © 2025 IEEE.
