N2  - With the advancement of research on multi-agent reinforcement learning, an increasing number of studies have begun to apply reinforcement learning to multi-agent path planning. This paper focuses on using distributed reinforcement learning for path planning and proposes an RAFO-A3C (Random and fixed obstacles A3C) multi-agent path planning algorithm for maps with mixed forms of fixed and random obstacles. The algorithm combines reinforcement learning and imitation learning, with A3C as the main training method and odrM∗ as an auxiliary. The algorithm learns decentralized strategies to plan coordinated paths in a partially observable world without the need for inter-agent communication. By introducing curriculum learning and multi-step penalty mechanisms into the RAFO-A3C algorithm, the trained strategies can be applied to environments of different sizes and obstacle densities without the need for retraining, and at the same time, avoid agents getting stuck in oscillatory ineffective behaviors. Finally, the algorithm proposed in this paper is compared with other multi-agent path planning algorithms, and the experimental results show its superiority in terms of success rate, completion time, and path length. © 2025 IEEE.
