N2  - This paper proposes an adaptive framework for coordinating multi-agent systems by integrating Model Predictive Control (MPC) and Supervisory Control Theory (SCT). The methodology uses extended finite automata with multi-objective cost vectors to enable dynamic, real-time optimization. Key features include a receding horizon strategy, online cost adaptation, and the integration of DES models with control logic. The framework's effectiveness is demonstrated through a case study on surveillance using Unmanned Aerial System (UAS), validating its applicability to real-time multi-agent coordination under performance-driven objectives. The main contribution is a unified framework that generates adaptive event schedules reflecting real-time cost dynamics, enabling decision-making in complex multi-agent systems. Copyright © 2025 The Authors.
