N2  - In nature, advanced organisms often complete complex tasks collaboratively through rigorous role division. In recent years, roles have been widely applied in multi-agent reinforcement learning (MARL) to enhance the behavioral diversity of agents. However, most existing role-based MARL methods require predefining the number of roles, which not only demands extensive prior knowledge but also leads to suboptimal performance. To address these limitations, we propose a novel Dynamic Role Learning in Multi-Agent Reinforcement Learning (DRoL) approach. Specifically, we take learnable role representations as inputs to the hyper agent network and adopt contrastive learning to adaptively learn the role representations of different agents, thereby achieving adaptive role learning. Experiments conducted on the hard and super hard scenarios of StarCraft II micromanagement tasks demonstrate that DRoL can reach the state-of-the-art performance level. © 2025 IEEE.
