N2  - This research study explores optimizing a Switched Reluctance Motor (SRM) for electric vehicle (EV) applications, designed with a rated power of 3 kW and a supply voltage of 400 V. The study aims to enhance crucial performance factors, such as torque generation, energy efficiency, and thermal management, all essential for reliable EV operation. A range of analyses, including electromagnetic, thermal, and vibrational assessments, was conducted to fine-tune the motor's performance. Electromagnetic characteristics like flux distribution and torque ripple were evaluated using finite element analysis (FEA), offering insights into efficiency and transient behavior. Vibrational analysis helped identify mechanical oscillations that could impact stability and longevity. Optimization strategies, such as waveform shaping and rotor adjustments, were applied to increase efficiency and reduce energy losses. This approach integrates thermal, structural, and electromagnetic perspectives, providing a comprehensive performance evaluation of the SRM. The results contribute to achieving higher torque density, improved thermal management, and noise reduction, advancing SRM technology for more efficient and sustainable electric vehicle applications. © 2025 IEEE.
