N2  - The safety and efficiency of intelligent connected vehicles highly depend on vehicle-to-everything (V2X) information exchange. To address the obstacle avoidance and decision coordination issues among multi-agent vehicles in dynamic environments, this paper proposes a dynamic obstacle avoidance distributed decision-making algorithm based on distributed reinforcement learning (DRL). First, a V2X perception model is constructed, fusing state information from vehicles, roadside units, and traffic lights to achieve global situational awareness reconstruction. Second, an improved multi-agent policy gradient (MAPG) framework is designed, utilizing local reward functions to coordinate individual optimality and global optimality. Finally, a dynamic priority scheduling mechanism is introduced to dynamically adjust the decision delay based on vehicle speed, distance, and risk level. Simulation results on the SUMO (Urban Traffic Simulation) platform show that in congested traffic scenarios, the algorithm achieves a collision rate of 0.067, an average high-density traffic efficiency of 0.78, and a decision delay increase of only 31.7% in high-density traffic scenarios. © 2025 IEEE.
