N2  - In heterogeneous swarms of Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs) and Unmanned Ground Vehicles (UGVs), leaderfollower schemes are commonly used for coordination but face challenges such as operational differences, communication constraints, and reliance on a single leader, creating a single point of failure. To address these issues, we propose a distributed leaderfollower model within a shepherding framework, dynamically assigning leadership among multiple agents. A UAV serves as an aerial shepherd, guiding a UGV that leads the swarm, while UGVs autonomously select local leaders to enhance cohesion and minimize communication overhead. An embedding-based observation history mechanism enables agents to leverage past data for improved decision-making. The model is optimized using an actor-critic reinforcement learning algorithm, refining agent behaviors through continuous learning. Simulations show a 72 % mission success rate, a 20 % improvement over cluster-based Boids, and a 12 % gain over learning-based methods, with collision rates below 30 % in swarms of 150 agents. These results demonstrate enhanced scalability, robustness, and coordination efficiency in large, heterogeneous swarms. © 2025 IEEE.
