N2  - In various business, industrial, and computational domains, a supervised common environment often provides shared resources for executing a collection of supported tasks. Multiple agents, acting as legitimate users, may repeatedly check in, select a task, and follow the designated workflow of the task to completion. Essentially, each agent continuously engages in a common alternative-paths workflow, where the workflows of individual tasks define the available alternative paths. Computer systems and interconnected sensor networks are widely used to collect sequences of observations from these agent processes, which serve as their behavioral signatures. For identity recognition in such an environment, a key computational challenge is to analyze the collected signatures and identify the most likely agents responsible for generating them. An anomaly is detected if the claimed owner of a process is not among the most likely identified agents. This capability enables the system to monitor agent behavior and detect potential security breaches. In this paper, we employ hidden Markov models (HMMs) to model the behavioral dynamics of agents engaging in alternative-paths workflows. Differences in agent behavior are characterized by distinct parameter values associated with the HMMs. We present a computational framework for identity recognition in this context and conduct experiments in the domain of text input using a circular keyboard. Our empirical results demonstrate the feasibility of this framework and its effectiveness for identity recognition in this domain. © 2025 IEEE.
