N2  - The Cross-border long-distance gas pipeline (CLGP) is a key energy corridor for China, ensuring energy supply and optimising consumption. With improved operational precision, allied decision-making is needed for pipeline health and gas transmission planning, integrating operational status, macroeconomic factors, geopolitics, and market forecasts. This manuscript introduces pipeline decision support system product (COTP), a generative AI agent based decision support system, enabling natural language interaction, flow transmitting simulation, and predictive maintenance for CLGP. COTP leverages multi-role generative agent technology to address gas transmission volume, pipeline operation, maintenance strategy decisions in CLGP. It operates through an autonomous loop of issue identification, code generation and work execution, output ranking, insight generation, and refinement. COTP relies entirely on natural language interaction, enabling users to initiate decision-making via prompt engineering, by agents outputting gas transmission plans, and with respect to corresponding maintenance suggestions if necessary. To enhance prediction and decision-making accuracy, COTP supports collaborative optimisation using voting and game theory achieved by multiple agents. It integrates multi-source heterogeneous data from internal and external sources via large models' online query capabilities, facilitating task breakdown and execution through deep thinking. A human-in-the-loop (HIL) design allows real-time user interaction during agent thinking and execution, ensuring decision-making aligns with user intent. COTP's steerability, user experience, prediction accuracy, and interpretability were validated using actual pipeline operating data, including historical CLGP scheduling reports, SCADA/PPS monitoring data, inventory levels, weather conditions, and commodity price fluctuations. 12 pipeline scheduling employers (6 online, 6 offline; 6 males, 6 females) evaluated COTP by comparing it with baseline methods-direct prompt-based generative AI and optimising computation for gas transmission decisions and maintenance strategies. Volunteers provided subjective and objective ratings on a 0-5 scale (strongly disagree to completely agree) to assess steerability, user experience, problem-solving, and refinements in terms of comparative studies over the task executed by COTP and baseline, respectively. All volunteers acknowledged COTP's steerability and user experiences, favouring its HIL, step-in interaction design over the baseline for enhanced stability. COTP demonstrated superior autonomous problem detection and robustness. Most volunteers agreed COTP enabled effective data-driven predictions and insights, while the baseline exhibited inconsistent performance and unreliable refinement ability. Although code generation category remain similar, it remained few existent since the baseline's overall process lacked significance. This findings verified that through innovative product interaction design, COTP has achieved fully natural language prompt driven co-planning, co-executing and decision-making processes, enabling autonomous execution and refinement. It provided simpler and efficient user-experience for complex decision-making in CLGP transition operation. COTP has distilled a more agile product interaction, leveraging rapid iteration capabilities of generative AI. By adapting to different target scenarios, it has potential to achieve rapid applications in equipment management, preventive maintenance, and spare parts strategy formulation across other domains. Compared to baseline, COTP's autonomous refinement capabilities offer more reasonable, feasible, and scientifically grounded solutions for complex decision-making challenges. Copyright © 2025, Society of Petroleum Engineers.
