N2  - This research proposes an innovative approach regarding evaluating community space by utilizing multi-agent system empowered by large language models (LLMs). Traditionally the way to evaluate space is to apply post-occupancy evaluation (POE) after construction that not only time consuming but requiring budget and manpower. By applying LLM Agents as a means for virtual simulations, this research proposes an innovative method allowing the physical environment be evaluated before construction The proposed system comprises a detailed community environment model, demographically diverse agent profiles, as well as a sophisticated action mechanism enabling simulation for realistic social interactions. Based on an initial experiment with seven virtual residents, this research successfully captures social nodes, movement patterns, and evolving social networks, representing behavior consistent with agents' demographic attributes. Consequently, evaluation costs could be reduced that provides valuable insights for design before construction. Future work of this research will aim at expanding the scale of simulations, enhancing the mechanism of social behavior, and exploring significant advancement in the evaluation of community design. © 2024 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
