N2  - In recent years, auction-based allocation mechanisms between clients and suppliers have been proposed in the procurement sector. However, a review of the literature has identified a limitation in the simulation of the proposed mechanisms: it is assumed that participants in the auctions behave in a perfectly rational manner, which prevents accurately capturing the progression of the auction in a realistic environment. The goal of this paper is, through the combination of the DEVS formalism and multi-agent simulation, to develop a model for a combinatorial double auction that incorporates the various expected behaviors of participants in a more realistic setting. Through simulation, we demonstrate that the consideration of agents with different behaviors has a substantial impact on the auction outcome. This work is part of a broader project aimed at developing a simulation framework that facilitates the implementation of combinatorial double auction models in real-world environments. © 2025 Society for Modeling & Simulation International (SCS)
