N2  - We study the problem of multi-agent path finding with earliness-tardiness costs (MAPF-ET), which encourages agents to finish their tasks just-in-time, neither too early nor too late. Given the tasks and their due times for multiple agents, the objectives are to obtain collision-free paths that minimize the maximum or total earliness-tardiness costs. This problem is NP-hard to solve optimally for all these objectives. We present two complete and optimal algorithms developed from the existing literature. The first approach is based on a reduction to the multi-commodity network flow problem and then to integer linear programming. The second approach is based on the popular two-level conflict-based search. Theoretically, we prove the completeness and optimality of the proposed algorithms. Empirically, simulation results demonstrate that the proposed algorithms are suitable for different problem settings and are capable of computing optimal solutions within a given time. © 2025 IEEE.
