N2  - In response to the problems such as the broken reasoning chains and insufficient self-correction ability of large language models (LLMs) in complex logical reasoning tasks, this paper proposes a multi-agent self-reflection framework. It achieves distributed reflection and collaborative reasoning among agents through standardized API interactions. This framework consists of four major modules: task decomposition, agent cluster, API interaction layer, and reflection integration. It designs three levels of reflection degrees: local reflection, cross-reflection, and global reflection. It also implements agent collaboration based on API protocols such as reasoning chain sharing and reflection requests. Experimental results show that on datasets such as GSM8K (mathematical reasoning), COPA (causal reasoning), and PrOntoQA (multi-step decision-making reasoning), this framework outperforms single-agent LLMs (such as GPT-4) by 12.3%, 9.7%, and 15.6% respectively. Especially in high-complexity tasks, its performance advantage is significant. Ablation experiments verify that the API interaction layer contributes 31.2% to the reasoning performance. The study indicates that distributed reflection achieved through API interactions among multiple agents can effectively break through the cognitive limitations of a single model, providing a new paradigm for enhancing the logical reasoning ability of LLMs. © 2025 IEEE.
