N2  - In this paper, we introduce a groundbreaking extension to the Soft Actor-Critic (SAC) algorithm, called Multi-Agent Distributional Soft Actor-Critic (MDAC), specifically tailored to enhance multi-agent coordination in dynamic warehouse environments. The core innovation of MDAC lies in the use of a distributional critic network, which predicts the full distribution of Q-values rather than just their expected values. This approach enables more robust decision-making and fosters improved exploration in complex scenarios. Additionally, MDAC incorporates a multi-head attention mechanism within both its actor and critic networks, significantly improving the system’s ability to understand intricate state-action dependencies and relationships. This feature is particularly beneficial in high-dimensional environments where multiple agents interact simultaneously. The effectiveness of MDAC is evaluated in a realistic warehouse setting, where Automated Guided Vehicles (AGVs) and human pickers work together to complete tasks such as picking, delivering, and returning goods. To ensure practical decision-making, the framework includes task-specific action masks and dynamic task allocation strategies, which restrict actions to only those that are feasible in a given state. Stability in the agent’s learning process is achieved through a KL divergence-based critic loss, while its exploration capabilities are amplified with entropy-based regularization. Our experimental results reveal that MDAC outperforms not only the standard SAC algorithm but also other cutting-edge reinforcement learning methods. It excels in key metrics such as task completion rates, operational efficiency, and agent coordination. Furthermore, the model demonstrates exceptional robustness when faced with task uncertainty and fluctuating environmental conditions. This work offers a significant step forward in optimizing multi-agent systems for real-world applications. By enhancing the efficiency and scalability of operations in intelligent warehouses and autonomous logistics systems, MDAC lays a strong foundation for future advancements in this critical field. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
